SIMPLE: flutter
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flutter
<hw>Flut"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
vibrate or move quickly; <as>as, a bird <ex>flutters</ex> its
wings</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To drive in disorder; to throw into
confusion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Like an eagle in a dovecote, I⟦br⟧
<qex>Fluttered</qex> your Volscians in Corioli.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flutter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flutter
<hw>Flut"ter</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of fluttering;
quick and irregular motion; vibration; <as>as, the <ex>flutter</ex> of a
fan</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> The chirp and <qex>flutter</qex> of some single bird</q>
<rj><qau>Milnes. .</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hurry; tumult; agitation of the mind; confusion;
disorder.</def> <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Flutter wheel</b></col>, <cd>a water wheel placed below a
fall or in a chute where rapidly moving water strikes the tips of the
floats; -- so called from the spattering, and the fluttering noise it
makes.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flutterer</ent>⟦br⟧
